/wiki/Pierce_County,_North_Dakota: Pierce County is a county in the U.S. state of North Dakota. As of the 2010 United States Census, the population was 4,357. Its county seat is Rugby.
/wiki/Stutsman_County,_North_Dakota: Stutsman County is a county in the U.S. state of North Dakota. As of the 2010 United States Census, the population was 21,100. Its county seat is Jamestown.
/wiki/Cavalier_County,_North_Dakota:
Cavalier County is a county in the U.S. state of North Dakota. It is south of the Canada–US border with Manitoba. As of the 2010 United States Census, the population was 3,993. Its county seat is Langdon. 
The city of Cavalier is in nearby Pembina County.
/wiki/Mountrail_County,_North_Dakota: Mountrail County is a county in the northwestern part of North Dakota, United States. As of the 2010 United States Census, the population was 7,673. Its county seat is Stanley. The county was originally created in 1873, then removed in 1892, annexed by Ward County. It was re-created and organized in 1909.
/wiki/Cass_County,_North_Dakota: Cass County is a county in the U.S. state of North Dakota. As of the 2010 United States Census, the population was 149,778, and was estimated to be 181,516 in 2018. Cass County is the most populous county in North Dakota, accounting for nearly 23% of the state's population in 2018. Its county seat is Fargo, the most populous city in the state.
/wiki/Sheridan_County,_North_Dakota: Sheridan County is a county located in the U.S. state of North Dakota. As of the 2010 census, the population was 1,321, making it the third-least populous county in North Dakota. Its county seat is McClusky.
/wiki/Ransom_County,_North_Dakota: Ransom County is a county in the U.S. state of North Dakota. As of the 2010 United States Census, the population was 5,457. Its county seat is Lisbon.

/wiki/Emmons_County,_North_Dakota: Emmons County is a county in the U.S. state of North Dakota. As of the 2010 United States Census, the population was 3,550. Its county seat has been Linton since 1899.
/wiki/Hettinger_County,_North_Dakota: Hettinger County (/ˈhɛtɪŋɡər/ HET-ing-gər) is a county in the U.S. state of North Dakota. As of the 2010 United States Census, the population was 2,477. Its county seat is Mott.
/wiki/Burleigh_County,_North_Dakota: Burleigh County is a county in the U.S. state of North Dakota. As of the 2010 United States Census, the population was 81,308, making it the second-most populous county in North Dakota. Its county seat is Bismarck, the state capital. The county was named for Dakota Territory political figure Walter A. Burleigh.
/wiki/Kidder_County,_North_Dakota: Kidder County is a county located in the U.S. state of North Dakota.  As of the 2010 census, the population was 2,435. Its county seat is Steele.
/wiki/East_Fork_Township,_Benson_County,: East Fork Township is a civil township in Benson County, North Dakota, United States.  As of the 2000 census, its population was 36.
/wiki/Benson_County,_North_Dakota: Benson County is a county in the U.S. state of North Dakota. As of the 2010 United States Census, the population was 6,660. Its county seat is Minnewaukan. The county was created on March 9, 1883 by the Dakota Territory legislature, and was named for Bertil W. Benson, a Dakota Territory legislator at the time. The county government was organized on June 4, 1884, and its boundary lines were altered by two legislative actions in 1885.
/wiki/Williams_County,_North_Dakota: Williams County is a county in the U.S. state of North Dakota. As of the 2010 United States Census, the population was 22,398. Its county seat is Williston.  Between 2010 and 2018, according to Census Bureau estimates, it was the second fastest growing county in the United States, trailing only neighboring McKenzie County, to its south.
/wiki/Dickey_County,_North_Dakota: Dickey County is a county in the U.S. state of North Dakota. As of the 2010 United States Census, the population was 5,289. Its county seat is Ellendale.
/wiki/Grant_County,_North_Dakota: Grant County is a county in the U.S. state of North Dakota. As of the 2010 United States Census, the population was 2,394. Its county seat is Carson.
/wiki/Fertile_Township,_Walsh_County,_No: Fertile Township is a township in Walsh County, North Dakota. 51.6% (127) of the population are male, and the other 48.4% (119) are female.
/wiki/Walsh_County,_North_Dakota: Walsh County is a county in the U.S. state of North Dakota. As of the 2010 United States Census, the population was 11,119. Its county seat is Grafton.
/wiki/Griggs_County,_North_Dakota: Griggs County is a county in the U.S. state of North Dakota. As of the 2010 United States Census, the population was 2,420. Its county seat is Cooperstown.
/wiki/Traill_County,_North_Dakota: Traill County is a county in the U.S. state of North Dakota. As of the 2010 United States Census listed the population at 8,121. Its county seat is Hillsboro, and its largest city is Mayville.
/wiki/Wells_County,_North_Dakota: Wells County is a county in the U.S. state of North Dakota. As of the 2010 United States Census, the population was 4,207. Its county seat is Fessenden.
/wiki/Divide_County,_North_Dakota: Divide County is a county in the U.S. state of North Dakota. As of the 2010 United States Census, the population was 2,071. Its county seat is Crosby.
/wiki/McKenzie_County,_North_Dakota: McKenzie County is a county in the U.S. state of North Dakota. As of the 2010 United States Census, the population was 6,360. Its county seat is Watford City. Between 2010 and 2018, according to Census Bureau estimates, it was the fastest growing county in the United States, growing 114.3 percent. The county lies immediately adjacent to the Williston Micropolitan Statistical Area, although the Census Bureau does not include McKenzie County in that grouping.
/wiki/Eddy_County,_North_Dakota: Eddy County is a county in the U.S. state of North Dakota. As of the 2010 United States Census, the population was 2,385. Its county seat is New Rockford.
/wiki/Ramsey_County,_North_Dakota: Ramsey County is a county in the U.S. state of North Dakota. As of the 2010 United States Census, the population was 11,451. Its county seat is Devils Lake.
/wiki/McLean_County,_North_Dakota: McLean County (/məˈkleɪn/ mə-KLAYN) is a county in the U.S. state of North Dakota. As of the 2010 United States Census, the population was 8,962. Its county seat is Washburn.
/wiki/Martin_Township,_Walsh_County,_Nor: Martin Township is a township in Walsh County, North Dakota.
/wiki/Grand_Forks_County,_North_Dakota: Grand Forks County is a county in the U.S. state of North Dakota. As of the 2010 United States Census, its population was 66,861, making it the third-most populous county in North Dakota. Its county seat and largest community is Grand Forks.
/wiki/Nelson_County,_North_Dakota: Nelson County is a county in the U.S. state of North Dakota. As of the 2010 United States Census, the population was 3,126. Its county seat is Lakota.
